                     ). The morphology of CoHS was characterized by a nanosheet structure (Fig. 3
                     a). For exploring the effect of NCDs on CoHS morphology, varying quantities of NCDs (1, 3, 5, 10, 20, and 30 mg) were incorporated under optimized conditions (Tables S1–S3), leading to the formation of CoHS@NCDs electrocatalysts via a hydrothermal reaction at 140 °C for 12 h. Structural characterization of the resulting electrocatalysts was conducted using scanning electron microscopy (SEM). At lower NCDs concentrations (1 and 3 mg), incomplete formation of nanosheets was observed, with unevenly sized and thin nanosheets growing on the sphere (Fig. 3b, c). When the NCDs concentration was increased to 5 mg, nanosheets in the CoHS@NCDs-3 electrocatalyst exhibited uniform growth. However, with a further increase to 10 mg of NCDs, nanosheets in the CoHS@NCDs-4 electrocatalysts transformed into smooth small balls, reducing the gap between flower-shaped nanosheets and causing agglomeration (Fig. 3d). Upon increasing the NCDs concentration to 20 mg, a clustered petal-like structure with a diameter of approximately 5 μm was observed, accompanied by a further reduction in the gap between the nanosheets (Fig. 3e). Finally, increasing the NCDs concentration to 30 mg led to the transformation of the flower-like materials into microspheres, resulting in a more compact spacing of the nanosheets and a spherical overall shape, thereby reducing exposed active sites (Fig. 3f). Among the tested samples, the CoHS@NCDs-3 electrocatalyst exhibited an open and uniform structure with a large specific surface area, affording ample opportunities for active sites to interact with electrolytes. Consequently, CoHS@NCDs-3 electrocatalyst was chosen as the optimal sample for further analysis. Based on the above analysis, it can be concluded that NCDs can effectively regulate the morphology of CoHS@NCDs composite materials.
